== The Authors == 
[[Michel Bauwens]] is the Founder of the P2P Foundation and works in collaboration with a global group of researchers in the exploration of commons-based peer production, governance, and property. 

[[Vasilis Kostakis]] is the Professor of P2P Governance at Tallinn University of Technology and Faculty Associate at Harvard University. He is the founder of the P2P Lab and core member of the P2P Foundation.

[[Alex Pazaitis]] is a Core Member of the P2P Lab and a Junior Research Fellow at the Ragnar Nurkse Department of Innovation and Governance, Tallinn University of Technology.

== Review ==

Elias Crim:

"In this article, I want to go beyond utopian reflections to what we might call eutopian proposals—i.e., proposals which (according to the Wiktionary definition of “eutopia”) bring us to “a place of ideal well-being, as a practical aspiration (compared with utopia as an impossible concept).”

And the particular eutopian vision I want to visit here is the P2P Foundation, an international network of researchers and advocates co-founded and headed up by the remarkable Michel Bauwens.

The P2P Foundation, now with over 15 years of visioning and collaborative research, has never been principally focused on politics, public policy, or the marketplace.

Instead, it could be described as a leading player in a global shift toward rebuilding and re-empowering a third force—namely, civil society—via what are called peer-to-peer (or person-to-person) global networks. (Reader reassurance: despite some jargon here, have no worries: what follows will not be super-technical.)

The arena in which the P2PF operates might be broadly described as the Global Commons which, according to author David Bollier, is “a shared resource, co-governed by its user community according to the community’s rules and norms. Things that can be managed as a commons include natural resources (land, water, air), and created assets (culture, knowledge), and can be either inherited or human-made, but ‘The Commons’ refers to the process as a whole — the synergy between the elements of a community, a resource and the rules for its co-governance.”

Thus the Commons, together with P2P systems, also represents a third mode of societal organization that evolves away from both the competitive market-state and obsolete, centrally-planned systems. This post-capitalist framework is based on the practices and needs of civil society at the local, regional, national and global levels.

In short, this is a movement toward a new political economy, no less, whose aims include ending biosphere destruction as well as promoting free (shared) cultural exchange rather than innovation-inhibiting patents, copyright, intellectual property laws, etc.

Given the breadth and depth of the P2P Foundation’s work, I want to limit this article to their recent Peer-to-Peer: A Commons Manifesto, a 70-page ebook describing how this shift to a new economic/social ecosystem is already underway in numerous seed forms and where it is going. (Another excellent guide to this transition is this work by Nathan Schneider.)

We might first note the punning title here: a commons manifesto is not a communist manifesto nor is there any statist agenda at work. After all we no longer live in the 19th-century world of the Manchester factories nor do we imagine that conventional central planning offers a path forward.

Moreover, rather than another example of technocratic, neoliberal “futurism,” the Manifesto draws inspiration from the kind of social economy which was once typical in most cultures around the world—indeed, the original sharing economy (not the Uberized phony version).

What’s being proposed here is nothing less than a new blueprint for our societies, one which is both commons-centric and which includes a new (technology-enabled) mode of production via peer-to-peer networks and platforms designed to allow us to collaborate and share.

Some here will ask: what’s the advantage in this notion of commons-based peer production (CBPP, as it’s called) over conventional capitalism?

First, its form of value creation works to integrate social, ecological and economic dimensions. It does so by enabling a new mode of production and property which help us transition from an extractive to a generative economic system. (The future development William Morris was hoping to see.)

How can CBPP promise such a vast shift? From the Manifesto:

Like the invention of the printing press before it, the Internet has created a historical opportunity for reconfiguring production, exchange, and the organization of society at large. The core emancipatory feature of the Internet lies in its capacity to massively scale up many-to-many communication, and therefore, in its capacity to lower the cost of self-organization and create and distribute value in radically new ways.

While much of the work of the P2P Foundation focuses on what’s called the emerging digital commons, the larger project here is not solely technological:

For us then, eroding capitalism points to the necessity of creating a prefigu­rative commons-centric economy within existing capitalism. The post-capital­ist future requires commoners as the agents of change, and in order to have commoners, the sphere of the commons needs to expand.

That is, historically, the commons referred to specific resources—an area of grazing land, a river, clean—in a specific locality. In recent years, the definition has gone beyond these “gifts of nature” to include civic infrastructure, cultural works and traditions, knowledge, and even bandwidth.

The umbrella movement over this work is called the Commons Transition and their website’s Commons Transition Primer is a well-designed introduction to these concepts, with substantial resources in all formats to go deeper.

It is striking how much of this work—sometimes in “seed forms”, sometimes in robust municipal projects—is no longer theoretical but already deployed in several European cities, notably Barcelona, Bologna, Naples, Milan, Frome, and Ghent. These developments in the urban commons (as the idea of a civic commons gains popularity) are bringing new civic platforms and a push for a “right to the city” (already incorporated into the Brazilian constitution)."
(http://solidarityhall.org/a-compelling-post-capitalist-blueprint/?)

